Here is more information on the proxy : ● Looking at your Cloud Function, it's a simple proxy that:
  1. Accepts a url query parameter
  2. Fetches that URL and streams the response back

  Curl

  curl "https://us-central1-ai-fb-poster.cloudfunctions.net/api?url=https%3A%2F%2Fexample.com%2Fimage.jpg" --output downloaded.jpg

  TypeScript (Chrome Extension)

  async function fetchViaCloudFunction(fileUrl: string): Promise<Blob> {
    const response = await fetch(
      `https://us-central1-ai-fb-poster.cloudfunctions.net/api?url=${encodeURIComponent(fileUrl)}`
    );

    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`Failed: ${response.status} ${response.statusText}`);
    }

    return response.blob();
  }

  // Usage
  const blob = await fetchViaCloudFunction('https://example.com/image.jpg');
  // Do something with the blob, e.g., create an object URL
  const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);

  Note: Make sure your manifest.json has the Cloud Function's domain in host_permissions if you're calling from a content script (background scripts don't need this):

  {
    "host_permissions": [
      "https://us-central1-ai-fb-poster.cloudfunctions.net/*"
    ]
  }
